17. Cron Jobs : to schedule commands or scripts.

Edit cron jobs:

crontab -e

List cron jobs:

crontab -l

Remove cron jobs:

crontab -r

Cron format:

* * * * * command

With "*" as: Minute Hour Day of Month  Month  Day of the week

Check cron service is ok: systemctl status cron

Example jobs:

Runs every day, every month at 2 AM:

0 2 * * * backup.sh >> /var/log/backup.log 2>&1, with 2>&1 to redirect the error output and also the standard output

Remove old logs with more than 7 days: 

0 3 * * * find /var/log -type f -name "*.log" -mtime +7 -delete >> /var/log/cleanup.log 2>&1

- Show usage of cpu and memory each 5 minutes: */5 * * * * top -b -n1 | head -20 >> /var/log/system_usage.log 2>&1

With "-b" executes top in batch (non interactive mode, it prints the info as text)
and "-n1" which says to execute only one time.  "-n5" will execute 5 times.

- Detect network problems: */1 * * * * ping -c 1 -w 5  google.com || echo "NETWORK DOWN" >> /var/log/network.log
with "-w 5" → wait maximum 5 seconds

18. at Command (One-time Jobs)

Schedule one-time job:

at 22:00

Then add the commands to run at that time, (Ctrl+D) to save it.


Example:

echo "maintenance task" | at 22:00
Output: job 1 at Thu Apr  2 22:00:00 2026 > job id and execution date given by the system

Or: 

echo "/home/ubuntu/db_migration.sh >> /var/log/db_migration.log 2>&1" | at 22:00

Or:

echo "systemctl stop myservice; /home/ubuntu/db_migration.sh; systemctl start myservice" | at 22:00

Viewing scheduled at jobs: 

atq

Removing a scheduled job:

atrm <job_number>

Deletes a scheduled at job.

Note: You get <job_number> from atq.

