20. Disk and Partition Management

List partitions:

fdisk -l Shows all disks and partitions on the system

Inspect an specific disk:

fdisk -l /dev/sda

Partition tools:

fdisk : modern tool
parted : classic tool

Example:

parted /dev/sda
fdisk /dev/sda

Partition types:

Primary (Maximum of 4 per disk. Can be bootable)
Extended (A container for logical partitions. Only 1 extended partition per disk)
Logical (Inside the extended partition. Allows more than 4 partitions)

Example layout:

/dev/sda1 → Primary (bootable)
/dev/sda2 → Primary
/dev/sda3 → Extended
/dev/sda5 → Logical inside extended
/dev/sda6 → Logical inside extended

21. Filesystems

A filesystem is the structure used by the operating system to organize and manage files on a storage device.

Examples:

ext4 : Default
xfs : High Performance
btrfs

Create filesystem:

mkfs.ext4 /dev/sdb1 : formats the partition /dev/sdb1 with ext4. (Warning: This erases all data on the partition.)

Tip: Always backup data before creating a filesystem.

Mount filesystem:

mount /dev/sdb1 /mnt/ext4 : Mounts the filesystem on /dev/sdb1 to the directory /mnt/ext4

Check mounts:

df -h
mount | grep /dev/sdb1

Unmount:

umount /mnt/ext4

Persistent mounts:

To make a filesystem mount automatically at boot, you add an entry to /etc/fstab:

Example:

/dev/sdb1  /mnt/ext4  ext4  defaults  0  2


